      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Brisbane Property With a Swimming Pool: Compliance, Costs and Buyer Appeal
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A pool can be one of the most compelling features of a Brisbane home or one of the most problematic. How it lands with buyers depends on the suburb, the campaign and how well you manage the compliance and presentation side.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's climate makes a pool a natural feature of many inner-east homes. In suburbs like Morningside, Camp Hill, Carina and Cannon Hill, a well-positioned pool with a decent outdoor entertaining area is often a genuine drawcard for the family buyer market. But pools are not universally valuable, and they carry compliance obligations that sellers need to get right before they list. Getting both sides of the equation sorted early will protect your result and prevent a pool from becoming a liability during negotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How different buyers see a pool</h2>
      <p>The buyer's view of a pool depends almost entirely on their life stage and household composition. Families with primary school-age children tend to see a pool as a major positive, particularly in Brisbane's inner east where outdoor living is central to how people use their homes. For this buyer, a pool is not just an amenity but often a deciding factor when comparing otherwise similar properties.</p>

      <p>Downsizers and empty-nesters are frequently the other end of the spectrum. For a buyer moving to a smaller home with the explicit goal of reducing maintenance obligations, a pool can be a deterrent rather than a draw. The same is true for a significant proportion of investor buyers, who may calculate that the pool adds maintenance cost and compliance obligation without proportionally increasing rental returns or yield.</p>

      <p>The implication for sellers is that a pool changes the composition of your buyer pool, not just the price. A property with a pool will attract more family buyers and fewer low-maintenance seekers. If your suburb's buyer profile skews heavily toward families, this alignment works in your favour. If it skews toward retirees or investors, the pool may narrow your audience in ways that affect competition and therefore price. Understanding your buyer profile before you set your expectations is worth doing with your agent before the campaign launches.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Does a pool add value in Brisbane's inner east?</h2>
      <p>The honest answer is: it depends on the property, the suburb, and the condition of the pool. In established family suburbs across the inner east, a well-maintained in-ground pool in a good position relative to the home and outdoor entertaining area typically does add value and broadens competition. A pool that looks tired, has dated equipment, or has obvious safety issues is unlikely to add to the price and may actively reduce it by giving buyers leverage to push back on grounds of compliance cost or remediation.</p>

      <p>What matters most is whether the pool is presented as an asset that a buyer can use immediately without spending money. A pool that needs resurfacing, has old equipment nearing the end of its life, or has fencing that does not meet current safety standards will be used by canny buyers to justify lower offers. The question to ask yourself before listing is whether the pool, honestly assessed, is move-in ready or whether it needs attention before it becomes a genuine selling point.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pool safety certificate requirements when selling</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, pool safety compliance is a legal obligation when selling a property with a pool or spa. The seller must provide the buyer with either a valid pool safety certificate or a notice of no pool safety certificate before settlement. If you provide a no-certificate notice, the buyer takes on the obligation to obtain a certificate within 90 days of settlement. In practice, most sellers are better served by obtaining the certificate before the campaign begins rather than leaving it as an unresolved item during negotiation.</p>

      <p>A pool safety certificate is issued by a licensed pool safety inspector following an inspection that assesses the pool barrier, gate latches, self-closing mechanisms, and surrounding surfaces against Queensland's pool safety standards. If your pool does not comply at the time of inspection, the inspector will issue a non-conformity notice that outlines what needs to be rectified before a certificate can be issued. Sellers who leave this until the last minute can find themselves in a scramble to complete repairs under time pressure, which typically costs more and produces worse results than addressing compliance issues before listing.</p>

      <p>It is worth noting that pool safety requirements in Queensland have changed over time and the current standards are more stringent than what many older pools were built to. A pool that has not been formally inspected in recent years should be assessed well before you intend to list. Budget time for any required rectification work.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Ongoing cost disclosures buyers expect</h2>
      <p>Buyers purchasing a property with a pool understand that there are ongoing costs, and the more transparent you are about them the less ammunition buyers have to manufacture uncertainty during negotiation. Buyers will factor in chemical costs, electricity for the pump, filter cleaning and servicing, and the eventual cost of equipment replacement into their thinking. In Brisbane's climate, an in-ground pool with an effective heating system, a variable-speed pump and a water-efficient design will have materially lower operating costs than an older setup, and this is worth communicating in your marketing if it applies to your property.</p>

      <p>If you have service records for the pool equipment, have them ready. A documented service history reassures buyers that the equipment has been maintained and gives them confidence that they are not inheriting a pool that is about to need major work. If the equipment is older, get a pool technician to assess its condition before you list. Knowing what you are dealing with, and either addressing it or disclosing it proactively, puts you in a far stronger position than having a buyer discover issues during their own pre-purchase inspection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Presenting a pool in your campaign: summer versus winter</h2>
      <p>Campaign timing affects how a pool photographs and how buyers experience it at open homes. A pool that is well-presented in the height of summer, surrounded by lush garden, sparkling water and a styled outdoor entertaining space, is a genuinely compelling element of your marketing. In winter, the same pool can look uninviting if the water is cold, the light is flat, and the surrounding garden is at its annual low point.</p>

      <p>Timing your listing for the warmer months can help your pool contribute more to the campaign. But if you are listing in winter or autumn, invest in making the outdoor space and pool surrounds look their best regardless. Remove any algae, clean the tiles, balance the water chemistry for clear appearance, and ensure the pool area is clean and styled at each open home. A pool that looks well-cared-for in the less flattering conditions of winter signals to buyers that the rest of the property is looked after too.</p>

      <p>For photography, ask your agent whether they recommend twilight or golden-hour shoots for properties with pools and outdoor entertaining. The warm light of late afternoon often presents water features and outdoor spaces more attractively than midday shots, and can significantly improve how the pool reads in the marketing images that drive online enquiry.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the pool is not compliant when you list?</h2>
      <p>Listing before your pool is compliant is a decision that creates risk throughout the campaign. Buyers who identify compliance issues during their inspections will use them as grounds for price negotiation or contract conditions. If the building and pest inspection turns up non-compliant pool fencing or a safety gate that does not self-close correctly, you can expect the buyer to raise it as a negotiation point even after an unconditional offer has been made.</p>

      <p>There is also a disclosure consideration. Under Queensland property law, sellers are required to disclose known material defects that would be relevant to a buyer's decision to purchase. A known pool safety non-compliance is arguably a material fact that should be disclosed rather than concealed. Sellers who are later found to have been aware of non-compliance and did not disclose it can face claims from buyers after settlement.</p>

      <p>The cleanest approach is to get the pool safety inspection done as early as possible in the pre-sale preparation phase, address any non-conformities, and obtain a current certificate before you list. It removes a potential negotiation pressure point, gives buyers confidence, and ensures you are not managing a compliance issue under the time pressure of a live campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Making the most of a pool in negotiation</h2>
      <p>A well-presented, compliant, and documented pool is a genuine asset in negotiation. It differentiates your property from comparable listings without one, and in a market where family buyers are competing, it can drive the kind of emotional conviction that produces strong offers. The sellers who benefit most from a pool are those who have taken care of it, presented it well, and removed the compliance and maintenance questions that give buyers reason to hesitate.</p>

      <p>If you have done the work and the pool is in good shape, make sure your agent communicates it clearly in marketing. Features like a recently upgraded pump, a new pool shell, or a heating system that extends the swimming season are worth calling out in the property description because they speak directly to the cost and convenience questions that buyers are thinking about even when they do not ask them explicitly.</p>

